caption: Really loved their veggie pot stickers! Probably one of the best of so many other Asian restaurants I've tried. Service was good - quick, polite, friendly. The ramen is also really good. On a super cold day, I wanted a hot bowl of noodle soup so I came to Ramen Utsuke! Upon entering at around noon, the place was about half empty so I got seated immediately. I got a bowl of red Tonkotsu (spicy pork ramen), and I asked to replace kikurage with corn which was done without a problem. The bowl of ramen was very tasty overall. It came with quite a few pieces of pork chasu which were full of flavor and tender; I was very impressed with it. The egg was also super flavorful and soft. I liked the spicy sauce too as it had flavor beyond just being spicy, and it was just the right amount on the bowl of ramen. The noodles were wavy which I really liked, but they were a bit overcooked. I would've given this place five stars if not for that. The soup was also quite tasty, and there was a load of corn in it. I really enjoyed it, and it was a good amount of food. It came out to be a little less than $13 post-tax, and the ambiance was pleasant and clean. The service was quite good too as our waters were filled repeatedly and we were asked how we were. I had a good experience here!

They immediately served us water without us even having to ask for it and quickly took our order.  My friend suggested the miso soup so  I asked if they can substitute the ramen noodles for rice noodles, and I was delighted that they could.  I ordered the chicken broth with the pork as my protein.  The broth was so amazing and the whole dish was delicious and satisfying.  I wanted to ordered an additional one to take home, but I prefer to eat it fresh.  The restaurant itself was small but comfortable.  It quickly began to get crowded, but that's a good sign that this place is good.  I don't visit downtown often, but when I do I would eat here again.

Finally got an opportunity to have lunch here and am I so glad we did. Location is good lots of street parking within 3 minutes walk from the restaurant. Everything we had was delicious Chicken karaage and  takoyaki as appetizers and Spicy Miso Ramen with pork broth and chicken as protein. The ramen was the best I have had in Maryland till date. Came across this place in a Facebook ad and looked it up online. Was initially excited - saw the menu and it had an entire page dedicated to ramen. For perspective, I love tonkotsu ramen - I try tonkotsu ramen everywhere I go. I’ve been to Osaka/kyoto and I (maybe unfairly) compare ramen everywhere else with that standard  I ordered the tonkotsu with straight noodles for $12. The broth was definitely lacking the richness and meatiness I expect from tonkotsu ramen. The straight noodles were most definitely not straight/handmade + it had the bite of instant ramen.  It was topped with the standard stuff - chashu, a soft boiled egg, black fungus and beansprouts. Personally not a fan of beansprouts in ramen (I consider them Chinese) but I’ve seen some ramen variants in japan offered with beansprouts. The chashu was seasoned + extremely tasty and was obviously prepared extremely well. I’m actually allergic to egg but I tried the egg to be a good reviewer, and it was a solid ramen soft boiled egg. Super flavorful, had the perfect texture with yolk slowly oozing on bite.  All in all, if you’ve never experienced a solid tonkotsu you could probably be impressed with the offerings here and find a lot of bang for your buck. Personally, the broth and noodles is what makes a good ramen, not the ingredients, so the gastronomical experience was lacking. The ambience was great and wait staff were friendly and helpful, but unfortunately I don’t go to restaurants for the wait staff, or even for value-for-moneyness - I go for life changing food and by that metric I was dissatisfied
